1
00:02:42,328 --> 00:02:43,852
Where's Harris?

2
00:03:00,613 --> 00:03:01,671
Mom?

3
00:03:08,254 --> 00:03:09,448
Mom?

4
00:03:16,396 --> 00:03:17,385
Mom?

5
00:03:22,001 --> 00:03:23,059
Hello?

6
00:03:28,274 --> 00:03:29,400
Hi, Mom.

7
00:03:30,243 --> 00:03:32,404
She keeps saying, "Where's Harris?"

8
00:03:33,479 --> 00:03:35,106
Who's Harris, Mom?

9
00:03:36,916 --> 00:03:39,908
Harris was my first mistake.

10
00:03:42,989 --> 00:03:45,822
Do you remember
your first mistake, Connie?

11
00:03:48,027 --> 00:03:50,518
Mom, you were dreaming, that's all.

12
00:03:50,697 --> 00:03:55,361
Your first mistake is like your first kiss.
You never forget it.

13
00:03:56,236 --> 00:03:58,204
Shh, just rest now, okay?

14
00:03:58,938 --> 00:04:01,600
You've never told us
about somebody named Harris.

15
00:04:01,674 --> 00:04:06,043
I guess I wanted it to be a surprise.
You used to like surprises.

16
00:04:07,914 --> 00:04:09,905
Was he an old boyfriend of yours?

17
00:04:11,084 --> 00:04:15,987
Mine and Buddy's. Buddy loved him, too.

18
00:04:18,825 --> 00:04:21,123
Harris and I killed Buddy.

19
00:04:21,995 --> 00:04:23,929
Mom, what are you talking about?

20
00:04:23,997 --> 00:04:26,989
Nina, she didn't murder anyone.

21
00:04:28,434 --> 00:04:31,335
Mom, look at me, look at me. Try to focus.

22
00:05:02,535 --> 00:05:03,729
Buddy!

23
00:05:04,704 --> 00:05:06,501
Hey, beautiful.
Hey!

24
00:05:08,941 --> 00:05:12,468
I've been on a bus for seven hours.
I'm not even remotely beautiful.

25
00:05:12,578 --> 00:05:14,603
You are never anything but.

26
00:05:18,151 --> 00:05:21,086
It's up to you to stop the wedding,
you know.

27
00:05:22,989 --> 00:05:24,047
Me?

28
00:05:24,624 --> 00:05:26,615
You're Lila's last hope.

29
00:05:29,896 --> 00:05:32,023
I'm not anyone's last hope!

30
00:05:32,365 --> 00:05:35,732
Shh, everything's okay.

31
00:05:35,868 --> 00:05:38,336
Connie, you're such a good mother.

32
00:05:40,239 --> 00:05:42,469
I wasn't much of one myself.

33
00:05:42,608 --> 00:05:46,669
No, you've been
a very good mother, sweetheart.

34
00:05:46,879 --> 00:05:48,972
Oh, fuck off.

35
00:05:49,782 --> 00:05:51,272
Come on, Mom.

36
00:05:51,684 --> 00:05:53,914
I'm nobody's sweetheart.

37
00:05:57,357 --> 00:06:00,258
It was a mistake to name that star after me.

38
00:06:32,058 --> 00:06:33,082
Hi, sweetheart!

39
00:06:33,159 --> 00:06:34,183
Hi.

40
00:06:38,164 --> 00:06:39,927
Honey, are you okay?

41
00:06:40,500 --> 00:06:43,298
Of course I am, it's my wedding.

42
00:06:44,070 --> 00:06:46,595
Come on, I'll show you to your room.

43
00:06:56,816 --> 00:06:59,751
I wasn't expecting anything quite so grand.

44
00:07:00,052 --> 00:07:03,385
It's just a very old dream
my family can't seem to wake up from.

45
00:07:03,456 --> 00:07:05,583
I don't look very Newport, do I?

46
00:07:05,658 --> 00:07:08,559
Honey, you look wonderful.
Where did you get this blouse?

47
00:07:08,628 --> 00:07:09,652
Oh...

48
00:07:09,729 --> 00:07:12,926
You always find the most unusual things.
Come on.

49
00:07:27,647 --> 00:07:29,080
Great dress.

50
00:07:29,882 --> 00:07:31,543
Bride of Dracula.

51
00:07:31,951 --> 00:07:34,818
Well, it's probably better if they're
more afraid of me than I am of them.

52
00:07:34,887 --> 00:07:37,822
Oh, no, my family is not scared of vampires.

53
00:07:37,957 --> 00:07:41,051
They don't have enough blood
to be of interest.

54
00:07:41,828 --> 00:07:43,591
Come on, I'll show you around.

55
00:08:15,394 --> 00:08:17,362
Trouble is, I need a first sentence.

56
00:08:17,430 --> 00:08:20,866
I can't believe that other guy got
"Call me Ishmael" before you did.

57
00:08:20,933 --> 00:08:23,834
I know, it's my luck, right.
But what do you think about this?

58
00:08:23,903 --> 00:08:26,929
"It was the best of times,
it was the worst of times."

59
00:08:27,607 --> 00:08:28,596
No good. No.

60
00:08:28,674 --> 00:08:30,266
I'll keep at it.

61
00:08:31,210 --> 00:08:32,837
So, your family owns this cliff, too?

62
00:08:32,912 --> 00:08:33,936
Mmm-hmm.

63
00:08:34,080 --> 00:08:36,412
Known locally as "the Plunge."

64
00:08:37,183 --> 00:08:40,949
I fully intend to amount to something
despite my advantages.

65
00:08:42,255 --> 00:08:43,620
Hey, look.

66
00:08:44,490 --> 00:08:47,118
Come on, I want you to meet somebody.

67
00:08:49,662 --> 00:08:50,890
Harris.

68
00:08:53,499 --> 00:08:54,488
Buddy.

69
00:08:54,767 --> 00:08:56,735
Buddy, come here.

70
00:08:58,671 --> 00:09:00,730
<i>Hey, the Fish is a wreck,
who's been taking care of her?</i>

71
00:09:00,806 --> 00:09:02,364
Nobody, probably.

72
00:09:02,441 --> 00:09:06,241
Ann, this is my big brother, Harris Arden.

73
00:09:06,312 --> 00:09:07,904
Dr. Harris Arden.

74
00:09:07,980 --> 00:09:09,971
The only one around here
who actually has a job.

75
00:09:10,049 --> 00:09:11,573
I'm not his brother. I'm one of the servants.

76
00:09:11,651 --> 00:09:12,777
No.

77
00:09:13,920 --> 00:09:15,410
I'm Ann Grant.

78
00:09:15,955 --> 00:09:18,355
Prone to inappropriate apparel.

79
00:09:18,858 --> 00:09:21,053
<i>If your family's not going to take
decent care of the Fish,</i>

80
00:09:21,127 --> 00:09:23,322
they should sell her to someone who will.

81
00:09:23,396 --> 00:09:25,489
What's wrong with it?

82
00:09:25,565 --> 00:09:28,693
Mold. Barnacles. The planks are leaking.

83
00:09:28,768 --> 00:09:30,633
Can we still take her out?

84
00:09:30,703 --> 00:09:31,829
Sure.

85
00:09:32,038 --> 00:09:34,131
Hey, Ann, you want to come for a sail?

86
00:09:34,206 --> 00:09:37,471
Oh, I think I have, you know,
bridesmaid things to do.

87
00:09:42,014 --> 00:09:43,504
Watch yourself.

88
00:09:49,789 --> 00:09:53,350
Pippin Fitzgerald,
I didn't even know that he was coming.

89
00:09:53,593 --> 00:09:55,083
Nine is good.

90
00:09:56,062 --> 00:09:57,427
Ann, darling!

91
00:09:57,496 --> 00:09:59,123
Hi, Mrs. W.

92
00:09:59,198 --> 00:10:01,564
Oh, lovely to see you.

93
00:10:02,101 --> 00:10:03,295
Oh.

94
00:10:03,603 --> 00:10:08,597
Ann, dear, it seems that half the people
I've seated together at this reception

95
00:10:08,808 --> 00:10:13,973
are either mortal enemies,
have had disastrous affairs, or both.

96
00:10:15,881 --> 00:10:19,715
I hear you're going to honor us
with a song at the reception.

97
00:10:20,152 --> 00:10:23,349
I don't think anyone's
all that likely to feel honored.

98
00:10:23,422 --> 00:10:26,983
Have you made your selection?
There are some lovely Schubert songs.

99
00:10:27,560 --> 00:10:29,892
That's not really the kind of thing that I do.

100
00:10:29,962 --> 00:10:33,454
<i>I can get through Time After Time
without going flat.</i>

101
00:10:37,103 --> 00:10:40,095
So, what are we gonna do?

102
00:10:40,873 --> 00:10:45,310
Why don't we move
Ellie and Joe Mortimer to table four?

103
00:10:45,945 --> 00:10:46,934
With the Fairfields?

104
00:10:47,013 --> 00:10:48,173
No?

105
00:10:49,081 --> 00:10:52,107
The tennis thing? Summer before last?

106
00:10:52,184 --> 00:10:56,621
Oh, my Lord.
At least one of us has powers of retention.

107
00:10:57,690 --> 00:10:59,385
Ann, did Buddy take you
down to the beach?

108
00:10:59,458 --> 00:11:01,289
Oh, yes. I met Harris.

109
00:11:04,030 --> 00:11:06,999
What are we gonna do
with those Mortimers.

110
00:11:07,066 --> 00:11:08,624
Oh, um...

111
00:11:10,069 --> 00:11:12,799
Here's a card from somebody named Peach.

112
00:11:13,572 --> 00:11:16,336
Peach Howze LaMott.
You know who that is?

113
00:11:17,076 --> 00:11:18,703
Sounds like a stripper.

114
00:11:18,878 --> 00:11:20,778
I don't think Mom knew any strippers.

115
00:11:20,846 --> 00:11:23,610
It's hard to say who Mom knew, isn't it?

116
00:11:23,683 --> 00:11:26,516
What's with this fixation of yours, anyway?

117
00:11:26,585 --> 00:11:28,143
What fixation?

118
00:11:29,922 --> 00:11:33,119
She mentions a couple of names
and suddenly you're Nancy Drew.

119
00:11:33,192 --> 00:11:35,752
Well, she keeps going on
about people we've never heard of.

120
00:11:35,828 --> 00:11:37,386
She says Harris was her only love

121
00:11:37,463 --> 00:11:40,432
and then she tells us
she and Harris killed somebody.

122
00:11:40,666 --> 00:11:44,500
She's not exactly in her right mind,
in case you haven't noticed.

123
00:11:44,570 --> 00:11:46,800
I have a feeling, that's all.

124
00:11:50,976 --> 00:11:54,002
Who was supposed to speak to Lila
about green?

125
00:11:55,848 --> 00:11:59,045
Hi, Ann. It's nice to see you.

126
00:11:59,118 --> 00:12:01,211
I'm sorry, I'm having a dress crisis.

127
00:12:01,287 --> 00:12:02,311
Oh.

128
00:12:02,388 --> 00:12:04,322
It looks better on Ann.

129
00:12:04,724 --> 00:12:07,818
Ann, darling, where ever did you get
those shoes?

130
00:12:07,893 --> 00:12:10,623
Oh, I don't know. The Village somewhere.

131
00:12:11,731 --> 00:12:13,358
You got them in a village?

132
00:12:13,432 --> 00:12:16,162
No, Greenwich Village, in New York City.

133
00:12:16,702 --> 00:12:17,691
Huh.

134
00:12:20,973 --> 00:12:22,941
I think champagne's going to be
beautiful with your hair.

135
00:12:23,008 --> 00:12:24,134
Thank you, Peach.

136
00:12:24,210 --> 00:12:25,609
This is going to be fun.

137
00:12:27,680 --> 00:12:29,147
I can't wait.

138
00:12:49,935 --> 00:12:54,565
<i>What good are words I say to you</i>

139
00:12:57,376 --> 00:12:58,741
You're on, baby.

140
00:12:58,811 --> 00:13:01,575
I don't wanna go on. I wanna go back.

141
00:13:02,848 --> 00:13:05,043
Sorry, no can do.

142
00:13:05,117 --> 00:13:06,744
I made a mistake.

143
00:13:06,819 --> 00:13:11,051
Mistakes are beautiful, baby.
Mistakes are part of the fun.

144
00:13:13,959 --> 00:13:16,086
I'm wearing the wrong dress.

145
00:13:16,929 --> 00:13:19,159
I can't go for a sail in this.

146
00:13:28,874 --> 00:13:31,741
I just think Mom
is trying to tell us something.

147
00:13:31,811 --> 00:13:34,541
I think Mom needs to be left in peace
at this point.

148
00:13:34,613 --> 00:13:37,480
Well. When I'm on my deathbed,
I hereby give you permission

149
00:13:37,550 --> 00:13:39,347
to ask me a question or two about my life.

150
00:13:39,418 --> 00:13:42,444
Nina, if you won't give Mom a break,
how about giving me one?

151
00:13:42,521 --> 00:13:44,921
This is probably not the best time
for us to have a fight.

152
00:13:44,990 --> 00:13:46,321
We don't need to have a fight.

153
00:13:46,392 --> 00:13:50,419
But really, I'm not going to let you
torture Mom anymore.

154
00:13:50,663 --> 00:13:52,062
Not at this point.

155
00:13:52,131 --> 00:13:54,599
Excuse me? Torture her anymore?

156
00:13:54,667 --> 00:13:56,794
Sorry, bad choice of words.

157
00:13:56,869 --> 00:13:59,861
So, I torture Mom, and you make her happy

158
00:13:59,939 --> 00:14:03,102
by getting the husband and the kids
and the big-ass house.

159
00:14:03,175 --> 00:14:07,271
Nina, don't ask me to apologize
for my life again, okay?

160
00:14:09,114 --> 00:14:11,582
Hey, look, here comes your life now.

161
00:14:11,650 --> 00:14:13,743
Ethan won't stop looking at me!

162
00:14:13,819 --> 00:14:16,379
Hey, Luc, why'd the monkey
fall out of the tree?

163
00:14:16,455 --> 00:14:17,479
Why?

164
00:14:17,556 --> 00:14:18,580
Because it was dead.

165
00:14:18,657 --> 00:14:21,057
Come on kids, let's go up
and say hello to Grandma.

166
00:14:21,126 --> 00:14:22,286
Is she dead?

167
00:14:22,361 --> 00:14:25,524
No, honey. She's resting, is all.
She'll be so happy to see you.

168
00:14:25,598 --> 00:14:27,293
Come on, let's go.

169
00:14:38,878 --> 00:14:41,506
You see,
she's just sleeping, is all.

170
00:14:43,115 --> 00:14:45,049
But she'll be dead soon.

171
00:14:45,618 --> 00:14:51,284
Well, she's had a good long life
and she loves you two more than anything.

172
00:14:54,360 --> 00:14:56,521
Can I touch her hand?

173
00:14:56,595 --> 00:14:59,029
Of course you can. Just be very gentle.

174
00:15:10,042 --> 00:15:12,374
What, is it time to go on?

175
00:15:13,412 --> 00:15:14,709
It's nothing, Mom.

176
00:15:14,780 --> 00:15:16,407
Where's my dress?

177
00:15:16,548 --> 00:15:19,142
Shh, just go back to sleep now, okay?

178
00:15:23,422 --> 00:15:29,292
When you were little, you used to cry
whenever I put that dress on.

179
00:15:29,361 --> 00:15:31,056
Do you remember?

180
00:15:31,130 --> 00:15:32,927
It meant you were going out.

181
00:15:33,565 --> 00:15:36,363
I never went very far, though, did I?

182
00:15:41,106 --> 00:15:43,540
I never went for that sail.

183
00:15:45,311 --> 00:15:50,010
I should have.
Oh, I should have gone for that sail.

184
00:17:08,627 --> 00:17:10,822
It's a little early, isn't it?

185
00:17:12,498 --> 00:17:15,899
This is Newport, it starts at noon.
Want one?

186
00:17:16,101 --> 00:17:17,591
No, thank you.

187
00:17:27,579 --> 00:17:28,807
Who's Harris?

188
00:17:28,881 --> 00:17:32,248
Harris. Harris is our old housekeeper's son.

189
00:17:33,118 --> 00:17:34,346
You're joking.

190
00:17:34,420 --> 00:17:35,580
Okay,

191
00:17:35,654 --> 00:17:39,283
this is not our family's summer cottage,
this is our family's summer mansion.

192
00:17:39,358 --> 00:17:42,418
And yeah,
Harris is our old housekeeper's son.

193
00:17:44,396 --> 00:17:46,159
In the summers
when we used to come up here,

194
00:17:46,231 --> 00:17:49,428
Harris and his mother lived
in an apartment off the kitchen.

195
00:17:50,335 --> 00:17:51,563
Really?

196
00:17:51,737 --> 00:17:52,897
Okay,

197
00:17:53,806 --> 00:17:56,274
it's time to shut up and dance.

198
00:18:21,500 --> 00:18:24,526
All right.
If fistfights break out during the reception,

199
00:18:24,603 --> 00:18:27,470
it won't be because no one worried
about the seating arrangements.

200
00:18:27,539 --> 00:18:28,699
Great.

201
00:18:31,210 --> 00:18:34,179
You will turn down that a little bit,
won't you, dear?

202
00:18:34,246 --> 00:18:35,770
Is your suit pressed for this evening?

203
00:18:35,848 --> 00:18:37,008
Mmm-hmm.

204
00:18:37,082 --> 00:18:39,550
And you need a haircut.

205
00:19:08,680 --> 00:19:10,705
<i>What a world, what a life</i>

206
00:19:13,085 --> 00:19:14,643
<i>I'm in love</i>

207
00:19:25,564 --> 00:19:28,055
We'll just feed them and get them to bed
and I'll be back later.

208
00:19:28,133 --> 00:19:30,567
Mommy, Ethan's farting! He's farting!

209
00:19:31,803 --> 00:19:33,668
Chloe, sit down, baby.

210
00:19:34,206 --> 00:19:35,298
Bye.

211
00:19:36,375 --> 00:19:38,502
Get your seatbelts on, kids.

212
00:19:40,279 --> 00:19:42,008
Sobering, isn't it?

213
00:19:44,783 --> 00:19:48,241
Didn't you say something a while ago
about wanting one?

214
00:19:48,554 --> 00:19:51,648
Well, after a bottle of champagne, as I recall.

215
00:19:52,224 --> 00:19:55,455
And in answer to a question from you,
as I recall.

216
00:19:57,663 --> 00:19:59,028
I mean it.

217
00:20:01,366 --> 00:20:05,860
Darling, could we discuss this some time
when my mother isn't dying?

218
00:20:06,338 --> 00:20:07,999
Yeah. Sorry.

219
00:20:09,841 --> 00:20:13,072
It just seems like maybe...

220
00:20:15,047 --> 00:20:18,483
Maybe this is a good time
to talk about some new life.

221
00:20:20,686 --> 00:20:21,914
I know.

222
00:20:24,756 --> 00:20:27,520
Listen. What if I didn't really want to?

223
00:20:28,827 --> 00:20:31,318
I don't mean just for now. I mean

224
00:20:33,165 --> 00:20:34,291
ever.

225
00:20:38,904 --> 00:20:42,840
Honey, it's time to shut up and dance.

226
00:20:50,682 --> 00:20:52,309
How's she doing?

227
00:20:52,384 --> 00:20:54,818
I don't know. Not so good.

228
00:20:56,688 --> 00:21:00,681
We just want to keep her out of pain now.
As much as we can.

229
00:21:01,727 --> 00:21:03,592
She keeps saying strange things.

230
00:21:03,662 --> 00:21:08,224
They do, sometimes, in end stage.
The medication can make them very dreamy.

231
00:21:09,368 --> 00:21:14,067
She's been talking about people
from her past, I guess.

232
00:21:14,139 --> 00:21:16,835
People my sister and I have never heard of.

233
00:21:16,908 --> 00:21:20,344
Well, they might be real people
and they might not be.

234
00:21:22,748 --> 00:21:24,648
You never really know.

235
00:21:36,962 --> 00:21:41,558
So, Mom,
this is all just a dream you're having?

236
00:21:50,942 --> 00:21:52,569
Hello, Harris. How are you?

237
00:21:52,644 --> 00:21:54,407
Hello, Mrs. Wittenborn.

238
00:21:58,450 --> 00:22:02,045
Seriously, Lila is making a big mistake,
don't you think?

239
00:22:03,055 --> 00:22:04,989
It's a little hard to say.

240
00:22:05,057 --> 00:22:09,391
All right, what do you like best about Carl?

241
00:22:13,432 --> 00:22:16,424
Go on, go on. Yeah, go on.

242
00:22:16,501 --> 00:22:17,866
Carl is...

243
00:22:19,871 --> 00:22:20,997
Tall.

244
00:22:23,809 --> 00:22:26,107
But you know, Buddy,
if this is what Lila wants...

245
00:22:26,178 --> 00:22:29,739
No, no, no. This is what Lila thinks
that she's supposed to want.

246
00:22:29,815 --> 00:22:31,282
There's a difference.

247
00:22:31,350 --> 00:22:33,545
Well, maybe not for Lila.

248
00:22:36,088 --> 00:22:37,453
I think...

249
00:22:39,658 --> 00:22:42,286
I think that she should marry Harris.

250
00:22:44,496 --> 00:22:45,588
Do you?

251
00:22:46,398 --> 00:22:47,888
He's the one she's really in love with.

252
00:22:47,966 --> 00:22:51,163
Has been, like,
ever since we were kids, you know?

253
00:22:52,771 --> 00:22:54,102
Is Harris in love with her?

254
00:22:54,172 --> 00:22:57,608
Everyone's in love with Lila,
