00:42:37,321 --> 00:42:38,583
I know.

512
00:42:44,562 --> 00:42:47,588
I need you to be a proper bridesmaid.

513
00:42:48,399 --> 00:42:51,163
I need you to be very, very nice to Carl.

514
00:42:52,570 --> 00:42:54,470
Can you do that for me?

515
00:42:54,538 --> 00:42:58,872
Is that what you really and truly
want me to do?

516
00:43:00,844 --> 00:43:04,507
He's a good man
and he'll be a wonderful husband.

517
00:43:06,684 --> 00:43:09,346
Now it's time to hit the deck, dear...

518
00:43:11,889 --> 00:43:13,049
Good morning, Ann.

519
00:43:13,123 --> 00:43:14,283
Good morning.

520
00:43:17,061 --> 00:43:20,394
Well, everything seemed
like a good idea at the time.

521
00:43:20,664 --> 00:43:23,326
One thing led to another.

522
00:43:24,868 --> 00:43:27,166
But now, when I look back on it all.

523
00:43:27,237 --> 00:43:28,864
What do you see?

524
00:43:30,608 --> 00:43:33,042
Waste. Failure.

525
00:43:34,211 --> 00:43:35,576
Only that?

526
00:43:36,313 --> 00:43:37,940
Oh, pretty much.

527
00:43:39,416 --> 00:43:42,647
Why don't you think of a time
when you were happy?

528
00:43:43,020 --> 00:43:45,818
Don't patronize me, please.

529
00:43:47,224 --> 00:43:49,692
Why don't you just close your eyes,

530
00:43:50,494 --> 00:43:53,258
and think of a time when you were happy?

531
00:43:55,099 --> 00:43:58,398
It's best, really
if you choose something ordinary.

532
00:44:00,638 --> 00:44:03,630
An ordinary moment during an ordinary day.

533
00:44:22,426 --> 00:44:24,792
Mommy, I want to go home.

534
00:44:25,362 --> 00:44:26,351
Oh, honey...

535
00:44:26,430 --> 00:44:27,692
Everybody's a critic.

536
00:44:27,765 --> 00:44:29,824
No, I'm a terrible mother.

537
00:44:31,535 --> 00:44:33,867
Connie, sweetheart, I'm so sorry.

538
00:44:33,971 --> 00:44:36,439
Your mommy just can't afford a sitter
today and tonight.

539
00:44:39,143 --> 00:44:42,010
Hey, you know I think
I should take her home.

540
00:44:42,079 --> 00:44:44,104
We got to rehearse, baby.

541
00:44:45,149 --> 00:44:46,844
Give her to me.

542
00:44:47,518 --> 00:44:49,884
I've had three, I know what I'm doing.

543
00:44:53,290 --> 00:44:56,123
Now look here. This is a piano.

544
00:44:56,193 --> 00:45:00,630
And you and me are gonna play it.
And your mama's gonna sing for us.

545
00:45:01,398 --> 00:45:02,797
Here we go.

546
00:45:19,416 --> 00:45:23,113
<i>Time after time</i>

547
00:45:23,420 --> 00:45:27,322
<i>I tell myself that I'm</i>

548
00:45:27,725 --> 00:45:33,459
<i>So lucky to be loving you</i>

549
00:45:34,865 --> 00:45:36,093
Look at Mama.

550
00:45:36,166 --> 00:45:38,293
<i>So lucky</i>

551
00:45:38,368 --> 00:45:43,465
<i>To be the one you run to see</i>

552
00:45:44,007 --> 00:45:46,567
<i>In the evening</i>

553
00:45:46,643 --> 00:45:50,340
<i>When the day is through</i>

554
00:45:52,783 --> 00:45:54,978
What happened to your dress?

555
00:45:56,754 --> 00:45:58,745
What dress would that be?

556
00:46:02,659 --> 00:46:03,785
Hey, Luc.

557
00:46:03,861 --> 00:46:05,328
Hey, Annie.

558
00:46:05,395 --> 00:46:06,953
How's the band?

559
00:46:09,099 --> 00:46:12,500
You know,
working our way up from dumps to dives.

560
00:46:15,205 --> 00:46:17,730
Connie, did you like my song?

561
00:46:19,309 --> 00:46:23,075
I'm Nina, Mom.
Connie went home for a little while.

562
00:46:23,147 --> 00:46:26,913
It wasn't right,
me dragging you around to clubs like that.

563
00:46:30,120 --> 00:46:31,815
Are you okay, Mom?

564
00:46:32,556 --> 00:46:34,387
Are you in much pain?

565
00:46:34,458 --> 00:46:36,892
We should let her rest a little, I think.

566
00:46:36,960 --> 00:46:39,986
I want to stay a minute, okay? Just me.

567
00:46:40,631 --> 00:46:41,723
Don't overtire her.

568
00:46:41,799 --> 00:46:43,391
Yeah, five minutes.

569
00:47:03,220 --> 00:47:04,482
Hey, Mom.

570
00:47:07,591 --> 00:47:09,115
How you doing?

571
00:47:10,127 --> 00:47:13,585
Honey, let's not talk about me.
How are you?

572
00:47:15,032 --> 00:47:16,329
I'm okay.

573
00:47:17,434 --> 00:47:18,594
I'm Nina, right?

574
00:47:18,669 --> 00:47:20,227
Of course you are.

575
00:47:20,537 --> 00:47:24,029
You look a little peaked, frankly.
Let me feel your forehead.

576
00:47:24,107 --> 00:47:25,472
I'm fine, really.

577
00:47:26,376 --> 00:47:27,866
No, you're not fine.

578
00:47:28,412 --> 00:47:30,812
I'm fine enough. I'm not the one who's sick.

579
00:47:30,881 --> 00:47:33,247
You're not the one's who's well.

580
00:47:35,586 --> 00:47:36,917
Can I tell you something?

581
00:47:37,187 --> 00:47:38,848
Of course.

582
00:47:40,257 --> 00:47:41,781
I'm pregnant.

583
00:47:43,627 --> 00:47:45,026
Oh, darling!

584
00:47:48,232 --> 00:47:49,597
That's wonderful.

585
00:47:49,666 --> 00:47:52,294
With Luc. Luc's baby.

586
00:47:52,903 --> 00:47:55,929
Our baby. I haven't told him.

587
00:47:57,474 --> 00:47:59,601
I haven't told anybody.

588
00:47:59,676 --> 00:48:02,907
And, Mom, I don't know what to do.

589
00:48:04,414 --> 00:48:06,848
I can't imagine getting rid of it.
I don't think I could do that.

590
00:48:06,917 --> 00:48:11,320
But I can't exactly imagine
being with Luc all my life, either.

591
00:48:11,388 --> 00:48:15,688
I mean, we've been together three years
and I've never felt sure.

592
00:48:17,561 --> 00:48:20,121
And now I'm two months along.

593
00:48:21,798 --> 00:48:25,495
I'm afraid having the baby would be
something I'd regret for the rest of my life.

594
00:48:25,569 --> 00:48:29,266
And I'm afraid not having the baby would be
something I'd regret for the rest of my life.

595
00:48:29,339 --> 00:48:31,500
A baby is a wonderful thing.

596
00:48:36,747 --> 00:48:40,843
You said Harris was your only love.
That's how I want to feel.

597
00:48:45,322 --> 00:48:48,348
Harris showed me how much it can be.

598
00:48:54,631 --> 00:48:55,962
Yeah, go on.

599
00:49:03,941 --> 00:49:06,239
Will you promise me something?

600
00:49:06,610 --> 00:49:09,579
Tomorrow, after Sis marries
Dwight D. Eisenhower...

601
00:49:09,646 --> 00:49:10,772
Stop that.

602
00:49:10,847 --> 00:49:14,374
...we can drive to New York together,
just you and I,

603
00:49:15,385 --> 00:49:16,852
and we go on a bender, you know.

604
00:49:16,920 --> 00:49:21,357
We hit a million clubs, hang around
with criminals and degenerates.

605
00:49:21,625 --> 00:49:24,219
I sing for criminals and degenerates.

606
00:49:24,294 --> 00:49:27,821
Thursdays through Sundays.
They lose their fascination.

607
00:49:28,432 --> 00:49:30,764
Hey, hey. Look. Look.

608
00:49:33,470 --> 00:49:34,994
Do you think there's a message inside?

609
00:49:35,072 --> 00:49:37,302
Sure, how could there not be?

610
00:49:38,408 --> 00:49:41,104
I'll bet you Carl threw a dozen of them
in the water last night

611
00:49:41,178 --> 00:49:43,169
for Lila to find this morning.

612
00:49:43,246 --> 00:49:45,908
No, it's for us. It's for you and me.

613
00:49:46,616 --> 00:49:47,981
Just you wait.

614
00:49:48,051 --> 00:49:51,020
There'll be a note in there
that says something like,

615
00:49:51,922 --> 00:49:54,482
"Lila, I'll love you forever."

616
00:49:55,892 --> 00:49:58,986
I was thinking more like,
"Whoever finds this bottle

617
00:49:59,196 --> 00:50:03,189
"gets to make three wishes."
So you start thinking of wishes.

618
00:50:06,103 --> 00:50:07,229
And?

619
00:50:10,774 --> 00:50:14,335
It's wine. It's really old wine.

620
00:50:15,045 --> 00:50:16,637
Don't drink it.

621
00:50:16,980 --> 00:50:19,107
Annie, I'm not that far gone.

622
00:50:19,182 --> 00:50:22,481
No, I'm sorry. Of course you're not.

623
00:50:41,838 --> 00:50:42,930
Hi.

624
00:50:43,573 --> 00:50:45,268
Look what I found.

625
00:50:45,642 --> 00:50:48,839
Oh, my God, her Queen of the Night dress.

626
00:50:49,546 --> 00:50:51,173
Do you remember her wearing this?

627
00:50:51,248 --> 00:50:52,613
Just barely.

628
00:50:52,682 --> 00:50:55,412
Whenever I think of Mom
I see her in this dress.

629
00:50:55,485 --> 00:50:57,476
Going off to work.

630
00:50:58,088 --> 00:50:59,487
She loved it so much.

631
00:50:59,556 --> 00:51:01,547
In her masochistic way.

632
00:51:01,992 --> 00:51:03,459
In a real way.

633
00:51:03,527 --> 00:51:06,792
Singing at the occasional wedding
was not what she had in mind.

634
00:51:06,863 --> 00:51:10,890
Do you remember
when she took us to hear Peggy Lee

635
00:51:10,967 --> 00:51:12,366
at the Algonquin?

636
00:51:12,436 --> 00:51:13,596
That was awful.

637
00:51:13,670 --> 00:51:15,035
No, it wasn't.

638
00:51:15,105 --> 00:51:16,834
Mom cried, hard.

639
00:51:16,907 --> 00:51:18,704
Because she was moved.

640
00:51:18,775 --> 00:51:21,710
Because she was sitting there
with two little girls in party dresses

641
00:51:21,778 --> 00:51:24,178
and Peggy Lee was the one
up there on the stage.

642
00:51:24,247 --> 00:51:27,273
Just how unhappy
do you need Mom to have been?

643
00:51:28,151 --> 00:51:30,142
Translation, please?

644
00:51:30,220 --> 00:51:32,688
Let's let it go. We're both exhausted.

645
00:51:32,756 --> 00:51:35,452
No. Let's not let it go.

646
00:51:37,961 --> 00:51:39,189
Great.

647
00:51:39,896 --> 00:51:41,056
All right.

648
00:51:41,131 --> 00:51:44,999
It seems to me that you're counting on Mom
to have been as unfulfilled as you are.

649
00:51:45,068 --> 00:51:47,093
And I'm not going to let you do it.
How dare you?

650
00:51:47,170 --> 00:51:50,367
I'm not going to let you badger her
on her deathbed

651
00:51:50,440 --> 00:51:55,309
about supposed old miseries
that are probably, in fact, just fever dreams.

652
00:51:55,378 --> 00:51:59,576
Who are you to tell me I'm unfulfilled?
Whatever the hell that means.

653
00:51:59,649 --> 00:52:01,844
Okay, so you're fulfilled and I'm not.

654
00:52:01,918 --> 00:52:04,352
The fulfilled one has the career
and the husband

655
00:52:04,421 --> 00:52:07,857
and the house and garden which just
happen to be three towns away from Mom.

656
00:52:07,924 --> 00:52:09,050
Mom needed someone close by.

657
00:52:09,126 --> 00:52:10,115
And cleaning women.

658
00:52:10,193 --> 00:52:12,525
You don't know how frail she's been,
these last few years.

659
00:52:12,596 --> 00:52:13,688
You've just breezed in and out.

660
00:52:13,763 --> 00:52:15,822
Family dinners at least three times a week.
And no more sex

661
00:52:15,899 --> 00:52:18,595
because even if you weren't too tired,
the children would probably hear you.

662
00:52:18,668 --> 00:52:19,657
Stop this!

663
00:52:19,736 --> 00:52:20,896
So I hope you'll understand if I tell you

664
00:52:20,971 --> 00:52:25,533
I don't look at you and say to myself, "Hey,
that's one fulfilled woman over there."

665
00:52:25,609 --> 00:52:26,837
Let's talk about your life then.

666
00:52:26,910 --> 00:52:28,309
Okay. Let's.

667
00:52:28,378 --> 00:52:30,812
You've had four different careers.

668
00:52:30,881 --> 00:52:32,906
Go-go dancing didn't count as a career.

669
00:52:32,983 --> 00:52:34,917
You were going to be a real dancer.

670
00:52:34,985 --> 00:52:38,944
Do you have any idea how hard it was
for me to admit that I was not good enough?

671
00:52:39,022 --> 00:52:41,286
I don't think you really tried, not really.

672
00:52:41,358 --> 00:52:43,792
Luc is your umpteenth boyfriend.

673
00:52:43,860 --> 00:52:45,589
How many, exactly, is umpteen?

674
00:52:45,662 --> 00:52:48,256
And you're about to dump him.
I look at you and I think,

675
00:52:48,331 --> 00:52:51,994
"In five years she'll have a different job
and another new boyfriend,

676
00:52:52,068 --> 00:52:54,366
"and five years after that,
she'll have another new job

677
00:52:54,437 --> 00:52:56,132
"and another new boyfriend."
So?

678
00:52:56,206 --> 00:52:59,607
Nothing gets its hooks into you.
You just drift.

679
00:53:00,844 --> 00:53:03,335
Well, something has.

680
00:53:08,685 --> 00:53:10,175
I'm pregnant.

681
00:53:11,254 --> 00:53:12,516
You are?

682
00:53:12,856 --> 00:53:13,845
Uh-huh.

683
00:53:18,595 --> 00:53:22,895
Sweetheart, sit down.

684
00:53:24,167 --> 00:53:26,362
Two months, Con, I can stand.

685
00:53:30,273 --> 00:53:32,070
A little slip-up.

686
00:53:32,375 --> 00:53:35,970
It can happen to even
the most determined commit-ophobes.

687
00:53:36,913 --> 00:53:39,074
Come on, sit down.

688
00:53:40,417 --> 00:53:43,409
Okay, I'll sit if it will make you any happier.

689
00:53:43,486 --> 00:53:44,714
It will.

690
00:53:51,261 --> 00:53:53,422
You could be a great mother.

691
00:53:56,066 --> 00:53:58,694
You really love your kids, don't you?

692
00:54:00,704 --> 00:54:02,467
More than anything.

693
00:54:04,407 --> 00:54:05,704
Got that.

694
00:54:06,643 --> 00:54:09,578
That doesn't mean
they don't drive me crazy.

695
00:54:09,779 --> 00:54:12,714
It doesn't mean
I don't wonder sometimes if...

696
00:54:14,084 --> 00:54:18,350
I should be a surfer chick
with seven stupid boyfriends.

697
00:54:21,758 --> 00:54:23,248
Got that, too.

698
00:54:55,892 --> 00:54:58,622
Will you not get mad if I say something?

699
00:55:01,398 --> 00:55:03,025
I'll do my best.

700
00:55:03,733 --> 00:55:06,201
If you go on being the bad girl,

701
00:55:06,636 --> 00:55:11,266
if you insist on screwing up everything
and everyone that comes your way,

702
00:55:12,275 --> 00:55:15,369
there's a very real chance
you'll end up alone.

703
00:55:19,582 --> 00:55:22,142
Nina, I'm sorry.

704
00:55:24,354 --> 00:55:25,446
See,

705
00:55:27,424 --> 00:55:29,255
at least I'm not mad.

706
00:56:32,856 --> 00:56:34,289
Hello there.

707
00:56:35,125 --> 00:56:37,593
What am I doing here? Who are you?

708
00:56:37,761 --> 00:56:40,025
I'm the night nurse. Remember?

709
00:56:42,599 --> 00:56:44,863
You said you've met my husbands.

710
00:56:45,068 --> 00:56:47,093
No, I'm afraid I haven't.

711
00:56:47,737 --> 00:56:51,173
I married Ralph Haverford.
He was the best man.

712
00:56:51,241 --> 00:56:54,642
Isn't that strange.
Do you think I took it literally?

713
00:56:55,612 --> 00:56:57,409
That I couldn't say.

714
00:56:57,680 --> 00:57:00,945
I left him on the sidewalk
like a piece of chewing gum.

715
00:57:01,017 --> 00:57:03,076
Some maid of honor, right?

716
00:57:04,120 --> 00:57:05,951
Are you feeling better now?

717
00:57:06,022 --> 00:57:10,652
Then I married Phil, Nina's father.
He had such nice hair.

718
00:57:13,430 --> 00:57:15,125
Nice hair is nice.

719
00:57:17,434 --> 00:57:18,867
Are you married?

720
00:57:18,935 --> 00:57:20,197
Yes, I am.

721
00:57:20,770 --> 00:57:23,238
Do you love him in that crazy way?

722
00:57:24,808 --> 00:57:27,368
We've been married almost 40 years.

723
00:57:27,944 --> 00:57:31,971
I've been married for 40 years.
More than 40. To Harris.

724
00:57:32,048 --> 00:57:34,881
I just haven't seen him the whole time
we've been married.

725
00:57:34,951 --> 00:57:38,717
Well, maybe that's the best way.

726
00:57:42,692 --> 00:57:45,684
Is there anyone special
you'd like me to call?

727
00:58:15,492 --> 00:58:16,754
Oh, Sis.

728
00:58:22,398 --> 00:58:23,660
You nervous?

729
00:58:24,133 --> 00:58:25,794
Yeah, a little.

730
00:58:25,869 --> 00:58:27,393
You look fantastic.

731
00:58:27,470 --> 00:58:28,528
Just breathe.

732
00:58:29,639 --> 00:58:32,767
Yeah, okay. All right.

733
00:58:38,181 --> 00:58:39,443
Peach...

734
00:58:49,792 --> 00:58:52,386
You think maybe Peach and Pip
could be next?

735
00:58:52,462 --> 00:58:53,895
Pip's a little stuffy.

736
00:58:54,230 --> 00:58:55,754
Peach likes stuffy.

737
00:58:56,232 --> 00:58:58,427
Hey. We're on.

738
00:59:02,872 --> 00:59:05,636
And then there's the question of Buddy
for Lizzie.

739
00:59:05,708 --> 00:59:07,801
Do you really think that
everybody in your wedding party

740
00:59:07,877 --> 00:59:09,936
should just marry everybody else?

741
00:59:10,179 --> 00:59:14,309
No. But it would be nice
if my wedding inspired another one.

742
00:59:15,285 --> 00:59:16,582
Ann.

